{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20882"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20882"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96912"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13757"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79527"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11793"},{"type":"tags","id":"12314"},{"type":"tags","id":"12707"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33147"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96912"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGenetic disorders can result from either abnormal protein structure or reduced synthesis of normal proteins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following genetic disorders is characterised by reduced synthesis of structurally normal proteins rather than production of abnormally structured proteins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duchenne muscular dystrophy","Hereditary spherocytosis","Sickle cell disease","Osteogenesis imperfecta","Thalassaemia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalassaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by reduced synthesis of structurally normal \u03b1-globin or \u03b2-globin chains. This distinguishes thalassaemias from haemoglobinopathies, which involve production of structurally abnormal globin molecules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions all involve abnormalities in protein structure rather than quantity:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuchenne muscular dystrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by mutations in the dystrophin gene leading to abnormal or absent dystrophin protein, which is essential for muscle fibre integrity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary spherocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E involves defects in spectrin, a cytoskeletal protein in red blood cells, causing abnormal cell shape and premature destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESickle cell disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a haemoglobinopathy characterised by a point mutation in the \u03b2-globin gene resulting in abnormal haemoglobin structure (HbS).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteogenesis imperfecta\u003C/strong\u003E results from mutations affecting the structure of collagen, leading to bone fragility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the distinction between disorders of protein structure versus protein quantity is important for comprehending the different pathophysiological mechanisms underlying genetic diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Genetic defects in nonenzyme proteins can have widespread secondary effects on multiple organ systems.","Haemoglobinopathies like sickle cell disease result from mutations affecting the structure of globin molecules.","Thalassaemias differ from haemoglobinopathies in that they result from reduced synthesis of structurally normal globin chains.","Structural protein defects underlie various genetic disorders including osteogenesis imperfecta, hereditary spherocytosis, and muscular dystrophies."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 148"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79527"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20882"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79527"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T13:11:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T13:11:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13757"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96912"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11793"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mendelian disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-12T20:19:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T20:19:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"